{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0,0,0.74,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78253"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10626"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63662"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26841"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are certain metabolic consequences with type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following occurs in insulin resistance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased lipogenesis","Increased glucose uptake by muscle","Increased insulin sensitivity","Impaired glucose uptake by muscle","Decreased hepatic glucose production"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance is a key pathophysiological feature. It leads to \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpaired glucose uptake by muscle\u003C/strong\u003E and adipose tissue, which contributes to hyperglycaemia. This is because insulin is less effective at promoting glucose entry into these tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased lipogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically seen in insulin resistance. Instead, there is increased lipolysis, leading to elevated free fatty acids in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of insulin resistance. In fact, the liver continues to produce glucose despite high blood glucose levels, contributing to hyperglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased insulin sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of what occurs in insulin resistance. In insulin resistance, tissues are less responsive to insulin, requiring higher levels to achieve the same effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin resistance in type 2 diabetes leads to impaired glucose uptake by muscle and adipose tissue.","Insulin resistance results in increased lipolysis and decreased lipogenesis.","The liver continues to produce glucose despite high blood glucose levels due to insulin resistance."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63662"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63662"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T09:12:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T09:15:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"